Create Models¶

Rubric 1: Create a logistic regression model and a support vector machine model for the classification task involved with your dataset. Assess how well each model performs (use 80/20 training/testing split for your data). Adjust parameters of the models to make them more accurate. If your dataset size requires the use of stochastic gradient descent, then linear kernel only is fine to use. That is, the SGDClassifier is fine to use for optimizing logistic regression and linear support vector machines. For many problems, SGD will be required in order to train the SVM model in a reasonable timeframe.

The classification task for our 2017 census dataset is to predict whether a given census tract has a high or a low unemployment rate. This is an important task, as it enables certain areas to be flagged as needing economic development or aid. Below, we first prepared our data for classification by cleaning it (in the same way as Lab 1), as well as removing unnecessary and redundant variables. We then split the data into training (80%) and testing (20%) sets. We created several logistic regression models with varying parameters, as well as some support vector machine models. We did an additional run of the models with an even further reduced dataset to compare performance.

At this point we have a clean dataset with no missing values, that matches the info from the cleaned dataset we used in Lab 1. Our target variable is "HighUnemployment", with 1 signifying a tract with a high unemployment rate and a 0 indicating low unemployment. We created the cutoff between high and low unemployment to be 6 percent, which was the median value for the unemployment attribute. By using the median to separate the groups, the classes will be of roughly the same size.

Since this dataset has 35 attributes, next we eliminate some unnecessary and redundant variables to cut down on the high dimensionality of the dataset. We still consider this to be our "full" model, however, since we retained 27 attributes.

# Function to print the results
def print_results(results):
    print('BEST PARAMS: {}\n'.format(results.best_params_))

    means = results.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
    stds = results.cv_results_['std_test_score']
    for mean, std, params in zip(means, stds, results.cv_results_['params']):
        print('{} (+/-{}) for {}'.format(round(mean, 3), round(std * 2, 3), params))

Stochastic Gradient Descent¶

We also performed Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) with Logistic Regression as a tool to improve performance and potentially improve accuracy. We first performed this technique on the full dataset, then on a reduced dataset using the most important features.

Stochastic Gradient Descent is done minimizing a function tracing a path of the cost function until it reaches a minimum value. In this machine learning the model is gradually updated to reduce the prediction error that follows. It requires two parameters: a. Learning rate - which limits the updates to correct the coefficient each iteration. b. Epochs - number of times to run through the training set to update coefficients.

The logic flows as below: First loop through the epoch Within this loop go through each training data for epoch for each update the coefficient for the epoch (repetitions) including the intercept.

We use numpy to the sigmoid function to arrive at the losses.

In [78]:
# defines the sigmoid function 
def sigmoid(x):
# calculates and  returns the sigmoid activation value for input x
    return 1.0 / (1 + np.exp(-x))
In [79]:
#defining the cost function here - uses sigmoid function to compute logistic regression cost
def cost_f(x, y, theta):
    t = x.dot(theta)
    return -np.sum(y*np.log(sigmoid(t))+(1-y)* np.log(1-sigmoid(t)))/x.shape[0]
# defined gradient cost which can also be alternately used.
def grad_cost(x,y,theta):
    t=x.dot(theta)
    return x.T.dot(y - sigmoid(t)) / x.shape[0]

Main part of SGD¶

In this part we do the training and update the model weights. The hyper parameter "learning rate" is set. It can neither be too small or too large so as to reach the minimum of the loss function. We can use values between 0 and 1 (randomly) and minimize loss and maximize prediction. If the difference between the last values of cost is less than the threshold, then we stop updating.

In [80]:
#defining the update function for training.
def update_theta(x, y, theta, lr):
    return theta + lr * grad_cost(x, y, theta)

def train(x, y, lr, iterations=100, threshold=0.0005):
    theta = np.zeros(x.shape[1])
    costs = []
    print('Started to train')
    for i in range(iterations):
        theta = update_theta(x, y, theta, lr)
        cost = cost_f(x, y, theta)
        print(f'[Training step number: {i}] — Cost function: {cost:.4f}')
        costs.append({'cost': cost, 'wts': theta})
        if i > 15 and abs(costs[-2]['cost']-costs[-1]['cost']) < threshold:
            break
        return theta, costs

def predict(x, theta):

def get_accuracy(x,y,theta):
    ypred=predict(x,theta)
    return (ypred == y).sum()/y.shape[0]

print(f'Accuracy -training:{get_accuracy(X_train_scaled, y[train_indices], theta)}')

Support Vector Machine¶

In the following code, we have created a few Support Vector Machine models to classify high and low unemployment, to compare with Logistic Regression. We first attempted to fine-tune the model parameters as we did for LR, but this proved too computationally expensive. # Evaluate models on the test set
def evaluate_model(name, model, features, labels):
    start = time()
    pred = model.predict(features)
    end = time()
    accuracy = round(accuracy_score(labels, pred), 3)
    precision = round(precision_score(labels, pred), 3)
    recall = round(recall_score(labels, pred), 3)
    print('{} -- Accuracy: {} / Precision: {} / Recall: {} / Latency: {}ms'.format(name,
                                                                                   accuracy,
                                                                                   precision,
                                                                                   recall,
                                                                                   round((end - start)*1000, 1)))

Model Advantages¶

Rubric 2: Discuss the advantages of each model for each classification task. Does one type of model offer superior performance over another in terms of prediction accuracy? In terms of training time or efficiency? Explain in detail.

As seen in detail above, in the full model, Logistic Regression performed better than SVM in all areas with an accuracy of 74.89%, recall of 70.36% and precision of 76.44%. In addition latency for SVM is very high and is very slow to train.

In the reduced model with features from PCA, Logistic Regression performed better with an accuracy of 71.1% and precision of 69.4%. Furthermore, LR with SGD on a reduced dataset had a higher accuracy of 72.2%. However, SVM performed better in recall with 74%. Also latency for SVM is very high and is very slow to train.

These indicate that Logistic Regression has most advantages over SVM for classifying high and low unemployment rates in our dataset. LR offers far superior efficiency, as it was very quick to run and even adjust parameters. SVM took too long when trying to adjust parameters, and it still took upwards of 3 hours when creating only two models to compare. In terms of prediction accuracy, Logistic Regression also had gains over the SVM models. SVM did slightly beat out LR in the recall metric for the reduced dataset, so if we were most concerned about the true positive identification rate we might opt for that model. However, the gain there is so small there that the Logistic model still seems advantageous. All this is in line with the commentary below.

Logistic Regression:

When to use LR:

  • Binary target variable
  • Transparency is important or interested in significance of predictors
  • Fairly well-behaved data
  • Need a quick initial benchmark

Logistic Regression can be considered any time we have a binary target variable and if we are interested in feature importance or to have a better understanding of what's going on within the algorithm. It should be considered when there are not too many outliers, not too many missing values, and relationships that aren't too complex. It is great for as an initial benchmark model on a binary classification problem with fairly well-behaved data. It's relatively flexible, and it's very fast to train. While it doesn't usually generate the greatest performance, it does set a very nice benchmark to start.

When not to use LR:

  • Continuous target variable
  • Massive data (rows or columns)
  • Unwieldy data
  • Performance is the only thing that matters

Logistic Regression should not be considered when we have a continuous target variable. Logistic regression also shouldn't be the first choice if we have a massive amount of data. There are other algorithms that really shine when we have a ton of data. Logistic regression is a great tool for a fast, transparent baseline model for a binary classification problem. It doesn't do well with a lot of data or particularly messy data. It's also unlikely to give the best possible performance on any given problem.

Support Vector Machines:

When to use SVM:

  • Binary target variable
  • Feature to row ratio is very high
  • Very complex relationships
  • Lots of outliers

SVM can be used for both categorical and continuous outputs. One area where SVM really excels is when the feature-to-row ratio is very high. It's when you have a lot of features and relatively few rows. SVM is also quite good at untangling complex relationships. SVM also handles data with a lot of outliers quite well, because it only looks at the points closest to the line, so that outliers are kind of ignored.

When not to use SVM:

  • Feature to row ratio is very low
  • Transparency is important or interested in significance of predictors
  • Looking for a quick benchmark model

SVM should not be used if there are lot of rows and relatively few features. Typically, SVM will take a long time to train, and the performance really won't be worth it relative to other algorithms. SVM should be used when there are lot of features, but few rows, or when we have a lot of outliers, that we are trying to untangle. But it is quite slow to train.

Interpret Feature Importance¶

Rubric 3: Use the weights from logistic regression to interpret the importance of different features for the classification task. Explain your interpretation in detail. Why do you think some variables are more important?

Below we display the weights from our logistic regression model, as well as a graph visualizing their relative magnitudes. When creating the model, the attributes were normalized to have the same dynamic range, so these weights are actually comparable and the weights have magnitudes that reflect their predictive power in the logistic regression model.

For a binary outcome variable modeled by a logistic model, the predictor variables are assumed to have a linear relationship with the logit transformation of the response. This means that we can mathematically describe the influence of each variable on the likelihood of the response with odds ratios.

As an example, we see that the Poverty variable has a relatively large weight of 0.587. This means that the odds ratio for an increase in poverty by one unit (after being scaled) is $e^{0.587} = 1.8$. So when all other variables are held constant, the odds of a census tract having high unemployment is 1.8 times higher for the tract with the higher poverty rate than the tract with a poverty rate just one unit lower.

From just this example, we see that having a high weight in the logistic model corresponds to a high positive impact on the likelihood of a tract having high unemployment, while a high negative weight in the model reflects a large decrease in the likelihood of high unemployment (because $e$ to a negative power is a fraction, and the fractions get smaller with higher magnitudes).

Since all the variables have been scaled, interpreting all the variables individually like we did with Poverty is not incredibly meaningful, but we can certainly make comparisons between the variables based on their relative magnitudes and conclude the importance of the features. In this logistic regression model, we see that the variables having the largest weights are White, Hispanic, Black, Employed, and Poverty, meaning that these feature were the most important for classifying high unemployment.

The largest magnitude by far is from the White variable, and it is a negative coefficient. This means that the higher the white population in a tract, it is much less likely to have a high unemployment rate. We found many indications of racial disparity in our exploratory work in Lab 1, and this further confirms our findings. We were somewhat surprised that Hispanic and Black had relatively large negative weights as well. Though they do not have as much impact as the white percentage of the population, they do also have a positive impact on the likelihood of high unemployment.

In addition, it makes sense that the Employed variable had a relatively large, negative relationship with the response, because the response is measuring unemployment rates. While the percentage employed is not the direct inverse of the unemployment rate in a tract, they are certainly related. Finally, Poverty is impactful as well, but the weight in the model is positive. So as poverty percentages increase, the likelihood of high unemployment increases in the model as well. This makes sense because many people that are unemployed are likely in poverty, which makes the two variables very related. The data indicates that the rest of the variables have some influence on the model but not nearly as much as these five. Therefore we infer that these five are the most important features to observe when classifying high and low unemployment rates.

A support vector machine can linearly separate the data that at first glance doesn’t appear to be easily linearly separable. By adding higher dimensions to the data, a dimension were the data can be linearly separable can be found. The vector above below is the vector that is orthogonal to the plane the machine has selected to linearly separate the unemployment classes. So, if you were to take the dot product of the explanatory variables of a tract and the output vector, the result would tell you what class the tract would belong to. A positive dot product would result in the row belonging to one class and a negative dot product would indicate the other class.

The vector chosen to separate the classes into high unemployment and low unemployment uses the percent of people with professional jobs, the percent of people with service jobs, the percent of people that drive to work, mean commute time, the percent of people in the private sector, and income in thousands. Mean commute time has the biggest absolute weight followed by population percent in service jobs and then income in thousands. This indicates that these variables are important in determining the separation plane.

Income in thousands being important makes sense because if the median income is high in a tract it is less likely that large numbers of people will be unemployed in that tract. However, mean commute time and service jobs are interesting variables to have an influence on discerning whether or not the tract has high unemployment of low unemployment. It will be interesting to further analyze the relationship between these variables and unemployment rates.
